Boil a large #pot{} of @water{to taste}(salted).

Chop the @potatoes{3%unit(s)} into 2cm chunks.

Strip the leafy part of the @kale{80%g} from the stem. Tear into small pieces. Discard the stem.

Add the potatoes to the boiling water. Cook until fork tender, ~{12-18%minutes}. Add the kale in the final ~{2-3%minutes} of cooking time.

Drain in a #colander{} and return to the pot. Mash together with a knob of @butter{to taste} and a splash of @?milk{} or @water{to taste}. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Cover to keep warm.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic{2%unit(s)} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve, peel and chop the @shallot{1%unit(s)} into small pieces.

== Garlic Butter Sauce ==

Place a pan over medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, fry the shallot until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add the garlic and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Pour in half the @apple cider vinegar{½%sachet} and allow to evaporate.

Add @flour{1%tsp} to the pan and mix well to incorporate.

Stir in @vegetable stock powder{1%sachet} along with @water{100%ml}.

Bring to the boil. Lower the heat and mix in @butter{1%tbsp}.

Simmer until the butter has melted and the sauce has thickened slightly, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Remove from the heat and cover to keep warm.

> TIP: If necessary, reheat the sauce just before serving.

== Salmon and Peas ==

Place a separate pan over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Toss the @salmon{200%g} with @Cajun spice mix{1%sachet}, @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} and a drizzle of oil.

Once hot, add the salmon to the pan, skin-side down.

Cook for ~{4-5%minutes}, turn over, and cook for ~{3-4%minutes} on the other side.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw fish. Fish is cooked when opaque in the centre.

When ~{2%minutes} of cooking time remain, add the @peas{120%g} to the pan and allow to warm through.

== To Serve ==

Divide the colcannon between plates.

Serve the Cajun salmon and peas alongside.

Drizzle the garlic butter sauce over the salmon.